  "prompt": "What does it mean to have a high TLC level in a blood test?",
  "response": "TLC stands for Total Leukocyte Count, which measures the number of white blood cells (WBCs) in the blood. A high TLC level (leukocytosis) typically indicates:\n\n1. Potential infection or inflammation\n- Bacterial infections\n- Viral infections\n- Fungal infections\n- Inflammatory conditions\n\n2. Possible medical conditions\n- Immune system disorders\n- Leukemia\n- Allergic reactions\n- Tissue damage or trauma\n- Certain medications\n\n3. Specific conditions associated with high TLC\n- Pneumonia\n- Appendicitis\n- Rheumatoid arthritis\n- Stress\n- Pregnancy\n- Smoking\n\nNormal TLC range typically varies:\n- Adults: 4,500-11,000 white blood cells per microliter of blood\n- High TLC: Above 11,000 white blood cells per microliter\n\nImportant notes:\n- A single high TLC result doesn't necessarily indicate a serious problem\n- Context and additional tests are crucial for accurate diagnosis\n- Consult a healthcare professional for proper interpretation and follow-up\n\nA healthcare provider can provide a comprehensive evaluation of your specific test results.",
